  "text": "The structured organization is likely due to the orientated growth enforced by the boundaries of the microchambers. It has previously been shown that radially confining the growth of self-assembling cartilage tissues can enhance collagen fiber organization in the direction perpendicular to the articular surface [CITATION_1] . The authors hypothesized the enhanced collagen fiber organization was due to internal stresses created by the confined growth of the tissue. It is also possible that cell migration, which was directed along the microchamber walls, influenced the organization of matrix components during tissue self-assembly. It is well established that cells can reorganize ECM components during collective migration [CITATION_2] . In addition, it has recently been shown that 3Dprinted PCL microfibers can guide the growth of collagenous tissues in vivo [CITATION_3] . It is clear from live/dead staining over the course of the 4 week culture period that cells are initially localised in the interior of the microchambers, and subsequently migrate out of the microchambers and fuse with adjacent spheroids over the top of the microchamber walls (Fig 1 d, e ). After longer term culture, this leads to significant ECM production over the microchamber walls ( Fig 6 a-f ). The parallel collagen fiber orientation present in the superficial zone is likely due the directed cell migration that occurred over the top of the microchamber walls during fusion of the cartilage tissues aggregates. It should also be noted that along with the directing collagen fiber orientation, the microchamber system facilitates integration of the cartilage and bone regions. For example, it is challenging to integrate self-assembled cartilage onto flat 2D surfaces (supplementary figure 1) .",
